s, Bankrupt in America is the first work to trace how bankruptcy was transformed from an intermittently used constitutional provision, to an indispensable tool for business, to a central element of the social safety net for ordinary Americans. To do this, the authors track federal bankruptcy law, as well as related state and federal laws, examining the interaction between changes in the laws and changes in how people in each state used the bankruptcy law. In this thorough investigation, Hansen and Hansen reach novel conclusions about the causes and consequences of bankruptcy, adding nuance to the discussion of the relationship between bankruptcy rates and economic performance.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aBankruptcyzUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 7aBUSINESS & ECONOMICS / General.2bisacsh  abankruptcy.  acliometrics.  aeconomic history.  agarnishment.  ainstitutional change.  ainterest groups.  alegal culture.  asupply of credit.  ausury.1 aHansen, Bradley A., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Business and Economics 2020 Englishz978311070479208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020 Englishz978311070471608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020z9783110704518oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Economics 2020z9783110704624oZDB-23-DBV08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2020z97831106930960 cprintz978022667956340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226679730423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226679730/original  a978-3-11-069309-6  University of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2020b2020  